ass, H.A. \u201cThe Front-End of an Intelligent Linear Goal Programming System\u201d. In Proceedings of the 6th International Conference on Computer Theory and Applications, Alexandria \u2013Egypt, September 1996, pp.25-37.\nRasmy, M.H; Bahgat, R.M.; Attia, S.S \u201cTime-Cost Trade-off Procedures for Crashing Projects\u201d. In Proceedings of the MES 5th International Symposium, Vol. 2, Cairo \u2013 Egypt, March 1996.\nBahgat, R.; Costa, V.S.; Yang, R. \u201cARCH: A Parallel Execution Model that Minimizes the Search Space of Logic Programs \u201c. The Egyptian Computer Journal, Institute of Statistical Studies and Research, Cairo University, Vol. 23 No.2, 1995.\nBahgat, R. \u201cAn Image \u2013based Information System for the Archaeological Description of Stelae\u201d. In Proceedings of the Seventh International Congress of Egyptologists, Cambridge-England, September1995.\nBahgat, R. \u201cA Multimedia Information System for the Description of Scenes\u201d. In Proceedings of the International Conference on Digital Signal Processing, Limassol-Cyprus, June 1995, pp.640-645.\nAlexandrou, C., Bahgat, R., Papadopoulos, G.A. \u201c A Multimedia System for Archaeological Scenes\u201d. Short Paper in Proceedings of ED-MEDIA'95, Gratz, June1995, pp.734.\nAbbas, H.; Bahgat, R.; Rasmy, M. \u201dEvaluation of Constraint Logic Programming from an Operations Research Point of View\u201d. In Proceedings of the Third International Conference on AI Applications, Cairo-Egypt, January 1995,pp.302-313.\nAbdel-Aziz, A.; Bahgat, R.; Nassar, S. and Shaheen, S. \u201cFamilies of Parallel Logic Programming Languages\u201d. The Egyptian Computer Journal, Institute of Statistical Studies and Research ,Cairo , Vol.22,No.1,1994.\nBahgat, R. \u201cTowards the Standardization of Scenes\u2019 Description\u201d. In Gottinger Miszellen, Heft141, Gottingen, Germany, 1994.\nBahgat, R. and Saleh, F. \u201cAn Expert System for Filling Hieroglyphic Text\u201d. In AMSE Periodicals, Advances in Modeling & Analysis, B, Vol. 31, No.1,1994, pp.29-42.\nAbdel-Aziz, A.; Bahgat, R.; Nassar, S and Shaheen, S. \u201cImplementation of Pandora on top of Prolog\u201d. In AMSE Periodicals, Advances in Modeling & Analysis, A, Vol. 22, no.2, 1994, pp.39-53.\nBahgat, R. \u201cHierarchical Constraint Logic Programming for Scheduling Problems\u201d. In Proceedings of the Annual Conference on Statistics Computer Science and Operations Research, Institute of Statistical Studies and Research, Cairo, December 1993.\nBahgat, R.M.R.\u201cNon-Deterministic Concurrent Logic Programming in Pandora\u201d. World Scientific Series in Computer Science, Vol.37, World Scientific Publishing Company, ISBN 9-810-21251-8, 1993.\nBahgat, R.M.R. \u201cThe Pandora Deadlock handler Meta \u2013 Level Relation\u201d. In Proceedings of the Third Workshop on MetaProgramming in Logic, Uppsala, Sweden, June, 1992, pp.86-100.\nBahgat, R.M.R. \u201cThe Pandora Abstract Machine: an extension of JAM\u201d. In Proceedings of the Pre-Conference Workshop of the 8th International Conference on Logic Programming, Paris, France, June 1991.\nBahgat, R.M.R. \u201cPandora: non-deterministic parallel logic programming\u201d. PhD. Thesis, Dept. of Computing, Imperial College, Univ. of London, March 1991.\nBahgat, R.M.R. \u201cSymbolic Constraint-based reasoning in Pandora\u201d. In Proceedings of the 2nd International Conference of the OUG Artificial Intelligence SIG, London, October-90, IET Conference Publications, pp.67-83.\nBahgat R.M.R \u201cThe Pandora Abstract machine\u201d. Research Report Doc 90/1. Dept. of Computing, Imperial College, of London, January 1990.\nBahgat, R.M.R. \u201cSolving Resource Allocation Problems in Pandora\u201d. Research Report DOC 90/2. Dept. of Computing, Imperial College, of London, January 1990.\nBahgat, R.M.R. and Gregory, S. \u201cPandora: non-deterministic parallel logic programming\u201d. In Proceedings of the 6th International Conference on Logic Programming, Lisbon, June 1989, pp. 471-486.\nBahgat, R.M.R. \u201cTowards an Integrated don\u2019t-know stream-and-parallel logic language\u201d. Research Report DOC 88/1. Dept. of Computing, Imperial College, of London, Feb. 1988.\nAcademic achievements\n1991, PH.D.is recommended to the British Computer Society Distinguished Dissertation, UK.\n1986, Awarded Distinction in the MSC. course Examinations, Imperial College London.\n1985, Awarded the prize of \"Kuwait Foundation for the Scientific Advancement: for the highest cumulative GPA in Kuwait University, Kuwait.\n1981- 1985, Awarded \"First Honour\", in Kuwait University, Kuwait.\nPrincipal Investigator in JMSE, 530637-Tempus-1-2012-1-PS-Tempus-JPCR, 2012-2015 (extended to Oct 2016), the project aims to develop a joint MSC in software engineering and to implement it in the MEA partner universities.\nPrincipal Investigator in InfrArtSonic, INCO-CT-2005-015338 Project, 2006-2008, for using non destructive techniques in the analysis and documentation of artworks. As Assistant Director and then Deputy Director of CULTNAT, I managed several international award-winning projects in the digital documentation of the tangible heritage of Egypt, such as The Archeological Map of Egypt, The Architectural Heritage and Urban Heritage of Egypt, The Documentation of Scientific Islamic Manuscripts, and the Eternal Egypt Portal www.eternalegypt.org.\nThe Egyptian Partner (Principal Investigator) in \u201cMedMultiTrain\u201d, a MedCampus Project, 1994-95, for innovative Multimedia Training in a banking environment. The Egyptian Partner (Principal Investigator) in \"Electronic Roads in the Information Society\", an INCO-DC Project, 1998-2001, Research project on distributed multimedia systems and networking.\nEgyptian Team Member in \u201cDevelopment of Upgraded Science and Engineering Education in Southern Mediterranean Universities through the Use of Telematics Technologies\u201d, joint sponsorship between UNESCO Cairo Office and European Commission, 1998-2000.\nIndustrial experience\nJan09-Dec12, Senior Consultant, Center for Documentation of Cultural and Natural Heritage, Affiliated to Bibliotheca Alexandrina and supported by Ministry of Communications and Information Technology, located in Smart Village, Giza, Egypt\nApril 94- April 96, Consultant of Cultureware Projects, The Cabinet Information and Decision Support Center (IDSC), Cairo - Egypt.\nMarch 93-March 94, Consultant of Cultureware Projects, The Regional Information Technology and Software Engineering Center (RITSEC), Cairo - Egypt.\n1997, Consultant to Sakhr Company for Building Intelligent Scheduling Systems for Educational Institutes.\nProf. Dr. Hoda ElMaraghy\nTitle:\nMember\nProf. Dr. Hoda ElMaraghy is the first woman Dean of Engineering in Canada. She is an exceptional role model, mentor, and Distinguished Scholar. Her pioneering and innovative research in Flexible Manufacturing has positively impacted industrial productivity, competitiveness, and wealth creation in Canada and abroad. Professor ElMaraghy\u2019s contributions in engineering, research and education are well-recognized.\nDr. Hoda ElMaraghy is a Distinguished University Professor and founding Director of the Intelligent Manufacturing Systems (IMS) Center at the University of Windsor. She is member of the Order of Canada (2020) and the Order of Ontario (2015) for her outstanding achievements and contributions to knowledge and industrial advancement. Professor ElMaraghy is a renowned scholar and research innovator, an inspiring educator, leader and role model, whose seminal contributions have been recognized nationally and internationally with numerous prestigious awards and accolades. Dr. ElMaraghy held Tier I Canada Research Chair in Manufacturing Systems for 14 years. She received an Honorary Doctorate from Chalmers University in Sweden. Her current research includes manufacturing systems paradigms; evolution and co -evolution / co-development of products and manufacturing systems using principles of natural evolution. She supervised more than 120 researchers and has more than 550 publications. She delivered numerous keynote papers around the world and serves on several scientific journals\u2019 editorial boards.\nDr. ElMaraghy is a Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada (RSC), Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences (IVA), International Academy of Production Engineering (CIRP), Canadian Academy of Engineering (CAE), Canadian Society of Mechanical Engineers (CSME) and Society of Manufacturing Engineers (SME).\nProf. Dr. Said Megahed\nTitle:\nMember\nA Professor of Robotics, Dynamics and Control in the Department of Mechanical Design and Production Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Cairo University since 1995. He obtained a PhD in 1984 in Automation and Robotics from Paul Sabatier University, Toulouse, France.\nDr. Megahed was appointed as Vice President for Research, Acting President, and Vice President for Educational and Academic Affairs at the Egyptian-Japanese University of Science and Technology (E-JUST), from February 2013 to December 2015. He was also appointed Dean of the Institute of Aeronautical Engineering and Technology (IAET) in Egypt from September 2011 through September 2012.\nDr. Megahed's research interests include robot modeling, simulation and control, system dynamics, and vibration and has over 100 published papers in these areas.\nMr. Karim Awad\nTitle:\nMember\nMr. Karim Awad has been the CEO and Board Member of EFG Hermes since 2013, which is the leading investment bank in the Arab world with business covering eight different markets serving its clients in the region and around the world. Since taking office in 2013, Karim Awad has contributed to restoring the company's profitability by creating a huge chain of investment businesses in the region's markets. Awad also holds the position of Vice-Chairman of the Board of Directors of EFG Hermes Eva, and a director in both the Nile Investment Company and Frontier Partners for Investment Management. He is also a board member of several companies. Prior to that, Awad held the position of CEO of the Investment Bank. Mr. Karim Awad won a seat among the most powerful CEOs of 2021 on the Forbes global list.\nProf. Dr. Khaled Ismail\nTitle:\nMember\nHe is the founder and Chairman of KI Angel, an Egyptian angel investment fund that invests in early stage 2011 start-ups. Dr. Khaled holds several positions. He is a member of the Board of Directors of Feather Invest, a member of the Leap Ventures Investment Committee, an advisor to the Egyptian American Foundation Fund, and a member on the board of directors of El Sewedy Electric Company (ZPASmart Meters) since 2014 until now.\nDr. Khaled joined as a member of the Presidential Advisory Council for Economic Development (2014-2015). He is the founder of SySDSoft (2003-2011), which was acquired by Intel in March 2011, and the managing director of Intel Mobile Communications (2011-2014). He also held the position of Senior Advisor to the Egyptian Minister of Communications and Information Technology (2004 and 2007).\nDr. Mohamed Hammady\nTitle:\nMember\nDr. Mohamed Hammadi has more than 30 years of experience in the field of communication, information systems and technology. He is Chief Technology Officer of Sky Group, Europe's leading media and entertainment company. Dr. Mohamed sets a Group-wide vision, objectives, and operating model for all European Sky territories in order to form a coherent Group-wide technology strategy. His team oversees all technology systems that support Sky TV services across Europe, broadband, mobile and digital platforms as well as key strategic programs such as cybersecurity. Dr. Mohamed also leads the Technology Executive Board, which reports to Sky's CEO. Dr. Mohammed is also a non-executive director of the UK's Standards Authority for Networks and Services Interoperability (NICC). He has also previously held a number of non-executive positions in French and Egyptian telecom companies and is an active member of a number of industry bodies focusing on business and trade.\nDr. Almoataz Bellah Ahmed Taha\nTitle:\nDirector of Technical Secretariat of the Board of Trustees\nAl-Moataz Bellah Taha is the Chief of the Minister\u2019s Office at the Ministry of Communications and Information Technology (MCIT) where he is responsible for driving, developing and monitoring strategic projects that are executed through the Ministry and its other affiliates, as well as participating in design and implementation of MCIT\u2019s strategy. He also holds the position of the Director of Technical Office at the Information Technology Industry Development Agency (ITIDA).\nTaha has gained extensive experience throughout his career. He held a number of positions including the Deputy Director for the Strategic Planning Sector at ITIDA, the Executive Manager for the Socio-Economic Performance and the Planning and Monitoring Sectors at the Egyptian Cabinet \u2013 Information and Decision Support Center (IDSC). He also worked at the Regional Information Technology and Software Engineering Center (RITSEC) and the General Authority for Rehabilitation Projects and Agricultural Development (GARPAD).\nTaha was a board member at Egypt Post and a current board member at Silicon Waha for developing Technology Parks, where he contributed in setting their strategy.\nTaha has earned his Doctorate Degree in Business Administration (DBA), with a specialization in Marketing from Ain Shams University in 2013, and a Master of Business Administration (MBA) from the Arab Academy Graduate School of Business of the Arab Academy for Science, Technology and Maritime Transport in 2009. He holds a Bachelor of Science in Technology Management and Information from the Higher Technological Institute (HTI), and an Information Technology Diploma from the Information Technology Institute (ITI).\nDr. Amr Ahmed Elmasry\nTitle:\nDean Faculty of Engineering\nDr. Amr Elmasry received the B.Sc. and M.Sc. degrees in Computer Engineering from the \u200eFaculty of Engineering at Alexandria University, Alexandria, Egypt, in 1991 and 1995, \u200erespectively, and the Ph.D. in Computer Science from the Computer Science Department \u200eat Rutgers University, New Jersey, in 2001. He worked as a senior researcher at Max-Planck \u200eInstitute for Informatics and as a full professor at the University of Copenhagen. Dr. \u200eElmasry has just been a full professor and the head of the Computer Engineering Department \u200eat Alexandria University of Egypt for the last six years. Through the years, he coauthored over 100 research \u200epapers.\nEducation\nPh.D. in Computer Science from Rutgers University\nCourses Taught\nData Structures\nAlgorithms, Discrete Mathematics\nArtificial Intelligence\nNumerical Analysis\nOperations Research\nPublications\nBooks\nhttps://scholar.google.com.eg/citations?user=DlSX_XcAAAAJ&hl=en\nJournals and Magazines\nhttps://scholar.google.com.eg/citations?user=DlSX_XcAAAAJ&hl=en\nProf. Mohamed El-Sharkawi\nTitle:\nVice President for Academic Affairs\nProf. El-Sharkawi obtained his Ph.D. in Computer Science from the Faculty of Engineering, Kyushu University, Japan. His research interests are in the area of Database Systems and Social Network Analysis. He has several publications in the areas of database systems and social network analysis published in international journals and conferences.\nEducation\nB.Sc. Department of Systems and Computer Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Al-Azhar Univ. - MSc. Dept. of Computer and Communication Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Kyushu Univ., JAPAN - Ph.D. Dept. of Computer and Communication Engineering, Faculty of Engineering, Kyushu Univ., JAPAN\nResearch Interests: Database Systems, Social Network Analysis\nCourses Taught\nDiscrete Structures\nDatabase Systems\nDistributed Databases\nPublications\nNariman Adel Hussein, Hoda M. O. Mokhtar, Mohamed E. El-Sharkawi:\nInfluential Attributed Communities Sea